Antibiotic Classes

Graphing antiobiotic trees

The primary clinical guidlines I’m expected to use are NHS Tayside - A Guide to Antimicrobial Use.

But this NICE guidance is also relevant:

  • Antimicrobial prescribing guidelines

  • Antibacterials, principles of therapy

NHS Tayside Formulary:

  • Adult Antibiotic Man

  • Formulary Abx Doses

NHS Tayside Area Formulary has a chapter (5), “Infections”. I’ve graphed this to show the grouped antimicrobials. Each chapter formulary subsection has an enclosed number (x, y). The first denotes a drug, the second a link.

See the full version here, Force Diagram.

See the full version here, Force Diagram.

The data I’ve been working on was collected from the formulary and formatted manually. I’ve worked out how to scrape this data automatically, but I’m still dealing with some formatting issues.

There are a handful of hierachy methods developed for D3. I’ve demonstrated Force-directed trees already, including the dragging effect.

I’ve also already tried a variant of Tidy Tree. I could reformat this a little to present it as a Radial Tidy Tree or Radial Dendrogram.

In order to do this I’ve reformated the data to work directly through D3. (Rather than an R wrapper).

1, Radial Dendrogram, 2, Radial Tidy Tree, 3, Tidy Tree, 4, Cluster Dendrogram.

If I add in some weighting data, such as prescription totals, I could also use a 1, Treemap, a 2, (Zoomable) Sunburst, a Circle Packing Diagram.

To do this I’ve also reformatted the data elsewhere with randomly calculated presciption numbers. You can see the full collection of graphics on Observable, here.
